==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sneak
<hw>Sneak</hw> <pr>(sn⟦emac⟧k)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Sneaked</conjf> <pr>(sn⟦emac⟧kt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr.
& vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Sneaking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>sniken</ets>, AS. <ets>sn⟦imac⟧can</ets> to creep; akin to Dan.
<ets>snige sig</ets>; cf. Icel. <ets>sn⟦imac⟧kja</ets> to hanker
after.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To creep or steal (away or about)
privately; to come or go meanly, as a person afraid or ashamed to be
seen; <as>as, to <ex>sneak</ex> away from company</as>.</def> <-- ?
<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> "snuck" is more common now, but not even
mentioned here. In MW10, simply "sneaked or snuck" -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You skulked behind the fence, and <qex>sneaked</qex> away.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To act in a stealthy and cowardly manner; to behave
with meanness and servility; to crouch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sneak</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sneak
<hw>Sneak</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To hide, esp. in a mean or
cowardly manner.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧[Slander]
<xex>sneaks</xex> its head.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Wake.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sneak</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sneak
<hw>Sneak</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A mean, sneaking
fellow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A set of simpletons and superstitious <qex>sneaks</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Glanvill.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Cricket)</fld> <def>A ball bowled so as to roll
along the ground; -- called also <altname>grub</altname>.</def>
<mark>[Cant]</mark> <rj><au>R. A. Proctor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sneak-cup</ent>⟦br⟧
